approach that it's like a PhD in marketing.
When you spend your time at Salesforce,  

723
00:59:46,960 --> 00:59:50,640
you're like, "This company is just one of 
a kind. It's a one of kind, and it's so  

724
00:59:50,640 --> 00:59:56,040
outlandishly good at one specific thing." And 
so looking back, all of these jobs have been,  

725
00:59:56,560 --> 01:00:03,280
when I say bingo card, I've just got an outlandish 
education in these areas that are not obvious at  

726
01:00:03,280 --> 01:00:07,360
all. And once you've seen them, they're like 
superpowers. They're superpowers to be able to  

727
01:00:07,360 --> 01:00:12,880
bring that same experience to bear on things. 
And so one thing that I really I'm trying to  

728
01:00:12,880 --> 01:00:20,240
figure out is why often people don't do that. And 
oftentimes people stay in a very specific domain.  

729
01:00:20,240 --> 01:00:26,400
They prefer to stay in a domain or they prefer to 
stay in a specific kind of type of company or a  

730
01:00:26,400 --> 01:00:31,440
role that works in a certain way, like companies 
that have the same operating model or they plan  

731
01:00:31,440 --> 01:00:37,680
the same way or they try to stay with things that 
are pretty similar. But it seems obvious that the  

732
01:00:37,680 --> 01:00:43,680
most likely way to really grow is the opposite.
It's to constantly be choosing things that are  

733
01:00:43,680 --> 01:00:48,640
either outside that, not totally outside the 
lines. Don't jump out of a plane if you've never  

734
01:00:48,640 --> 01:00:53,960
parachuted before. Obviously you want them to be 
in some way and adjacency, that you want them to  

735
01:00:53,960 --> 01:01:00,280
have something in common with what you know, but 
you want them to stretch you and change you. I  

736
01:01:00,280 --> 01:01:07,960
had a really transformative experience many, many 
years ago when I was at Atlassian and a guy called  

737
01:01:07,960 --> 01:01:14,880
Tom Kennedy, he was our general counsel, so chief 
legal officer basically, and a lifelong lawyer,  

738
01:01:14,880 --> 01:01:19,880
very smart guy. I liked him very, very much. But 
just a lawyer. Just a lawyer, corporate lawyer,  

739
01:01:19,880 --> 01:01:24,240
corporate counsel, I'm sure you know what they're 
like. And really great guy. And I remember,  

740
01:01:24,240 --> 01:01:31,400
so mostly in our meetings he didn't talk that much 
except about legal things. But I remember in one  

741
01:01:31,400 --> 01:01:36,840
meeting we were having this vigorous debate about 
a product strategy question about what we should  

742
01:01:36,840 --> 01:01:41,720
do. Should we go left or should we go right?
And as usual, he's there and he's mostly  

743
01:01:41,720 --> 01:01:45,760
just staying silent. And then eventually the 
conversation's been going on for 15 minutes and  

744
01:01:45,760 --> 01:01:50,880
he is like, "Hey, everybody, a year ago we talked 
about X, Y and Z," and he proceeds to lay out our  

745
01:01:50,880 --> 01:01:54,760
product strategy at that time, and he's like, 
"Just recently we said the following things,  

746
01:01:54,760 --> 01:01:58,840
and that was a product strategy, whatever. Now 
you are saying this. Isn't it obvious that isn't  

747
01:01:58,840 --> 01:02:02,680
this? What you guys are saying is not congruent 
with that, and if you really meant what you said  

748
01:02:02,680 --> 01:02:09,160
back then we should be doing X." And again, the 
room went silent, everybody kind of turned to him,  

749
01:02:09,160 --> 01:02:12,760
kind of nodded, and then everyone went, 
"Yeah, okay, I guess we probably should  

750
01:02:12,760 --> 01:02:18,200
be doing it differently." And so the meeting 
stopped when the GCE randomly mentioned that  

751
01:02:18,200 --> 01:02:24,200
he deeply understood our product strategy and he 
knew enough to be able to contribute in that way. 

752
01:02:24,200 --> 01:02:29,760
And so the life-changing part for me about that 
was just this realization that if I'm going to  

753
01:02:29,760 --> 01:02:34,840
be a really great professional, the type of 
professional I want to be is that type of  

754
01:02:34,840 --> 01:02:40,040
person. The type of person who can contribute 
to the whole company in all sorts of ways,  

755
01:02:40,040 --> 01:02:44,360
doesn't spend all of their time in everybody 
else's business, but understands the business  

756
01:02:44,360 --> 01:02:51,040
and has the mental horsepower and the experience 
to be dangerous in all sorts of, and I mean,  

757
01:02:51,040 --> 01:02:54,320
that in a compliment way. I don't mean that in a 
negative way, but to be dangerous in all sorts of  

758
01:02:54,320 --> 01:02:59,320
situations. I think that when you have leaders 
like that behind you and with you, then you're  

759
01:02:59,320 --> 01:03:06,240
just unstoppable. You're an unstoppable force 
in business when you have that motion happening.

760
01:03:06,240 --> 01:03:12,960
Wow, that was an awesome story and an awesome 
perspective. It's similar to the advice I always  

761
01:03:12,960 --> 01:03:18,400
give PMs of people always wondering, "Should I 
go deep on a specific subject? Should I just try  

762
01:03:18,400 --> 01:03:23,040
different things?" And I find just variety, 
especially earlier in your career is really  

763
01:03:23,040 --> 01:03:28,120
powerful, not just to help you discover the thing 
you like, but also to your point, just using  

764
01:03:28,120 --> 01:03:32,920
insights from all these different parts of the 
product and internal tools and trust and safety  

765
01:03:32,920 --> 01:03:39,440
and platform and consumer product side and growth 
